    <stitle>RECONDITIONING ROTORS - INSPECTION - HEAT-CHECKING</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="inspect" graphiccount="1">
        <title>HEAT-CHECKING</title>
        <para>Heat checks are short, thin, sometimes numerous radial interruptions of the braking surfaces of the rotor
            (
            <hotlnk xrefid="f0401816">Figure 16
                <xref refid="f0401816"/>
            </hotlnk>
            ). They are a normal condition of the disc brake function just as they are on brake drums. They are the
            result of the heating and cooling that occur as brakes are applied time after time. Heat checks are not
            detrimental to the function or performance of the braking system and no corrective action is required for
            this condition. Heat checks will frequently wear away and reform or they may progress into braking surface
            cracks, depending on such factors as the brake pad/rotor wear rate, brake balance, and how hard the brakes
            are used.
        </para>
        <figure id="f0401816" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g0401816" filename="../figg04/G0401816.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                     scalefitheight="272px" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 16. Heat-Checked Rotor</caption>
        </figure>
    </svcproc>
